teams.name: Friends of Bob Harris
teams.loan_because:
After stumbling into a job as a luxury travel writer, I saw so much poverty that I decided to turn those paychecks into Kiva loans. Then I visited a bunch of clients, who were amazing, and I've written a book about it called "The International Bank of Bob" (Walker/Bloomsbury, March 5, 2013).

I hope the book will get more people to feel a greater understanding of Kiva, a better appreciation of the role of microfinance, and most of all, more connected to the rest of the world.

teams.name: Daniel Bednarik
teams.loan_because:
Daniel Bednarik is the Senior Director of Molecular Engineering Unit (MEU) Operations at the Intrexon Corporation in Gemantown, Maryland.  He was previously Director of Genomics and Bioinformatics for Cardiome Pharma Corporation, and was previously co-founder and Vice President of Cardiovascular Biology of Artesian Therapeutics, Inc., which was acquired by Cardiome in 2005. He has served as a consultant for Cardiome for two years and was subsequently hired in 2007 to develop genomic and proteomic biomarker programs to help augment and accelerate clinical trial design. The primary translational derivative for Cardiome was creating the largest known cardiovascular gene expression database for Gene Logic.  Daniel Bednarik also served as a key scientist for the development of Human Genome Sciences’ (HGS) database and has over 28+ years experience in the field of virology with emphasis on HIV and herpes virus pathophysiology.  He was co-recipient of a DARPA contract in 2006 where he and his colleagues developed a novel non-host method for rapid vaccine manufacture and deployment. Daniel Bednarik is very experienced in developing and managing clinical programs.  His training was completed at Temple University School of Medicine (Philadelphia) in 1985, and The Johns Hopkins University Oncology Center (Baltimore).

Daniel Bednarik is very comfortable with both theory and application at the bench. On top of this foundation,  he has a deeply rooted enthusiasm and curiosity about new technologies and biological discoveries that I try to expand upon from my knowledge base relevant to biotechnology and scientific discovery tools and the commercial and therapeutic opportunities they offer.  Although Daniel is neither a physician nor a physiologist, he likes to seek out, absorb and integrate expert opinions in these and other key areas, being that he is a focused listener and a very quick study.  He strongly believes this method reinforces conception of creative ideas for both technical and experimental problem solving and for identifying new targets for experimental inquiry and potential commercialization.  Daniel is proactive and effective in facilitating interactions with industrial contacts that have benefited his collaborator’s laboratories programmatically in one way or another, and proactively tries to mesh his background and knowledge to complement those of the groups he collaborates with.  His prior and current collaborative relationships remain grounded in shared discovery goals, mutual benefit, and mutual trust derived from sustained and effective professional interactions.  As a result, Daniel Bednarik is delighted to engage in ventures that exploit these kinds of relationships while allowing these efforts to work together towards mutual scientific/therapeutic goals.

teams.name: Andrew Brunhart
teams.loan_because:
When CEOs step down, Andrew Brunhart steps in, leading practical change to transform organizational performance. Currently, Andrew Brunhart is leading the start-up of new functions for the Bureau of Engraving and Printing focusing on strategic change, portfolio and project management, order management and delivery systems, and quality assurance. Previously, Andrew Brunhart was Chief Operating Officer of the United States Mint charged with leading a turnaround to become a learning, accountable, results-oriented organization. Prior to this service, he was Chief Executive Officer of the Washington Suburban Sanitary Commission (WSSC) in Laurel, Maryland, the nation’s eighth largest combined water and wastewater utility serving 2M citizens of two counties. In that capacity, Andrew Brunhart led utility-wide turnaround efforts and guided revitalization of Engineering and Capital Programs ($1.5B) proactively addressing WSSC’s aging infrastructure via 1,500 employees. During his tenure, WSSC received recognition as one of the “Best Places to Work” in Maryland for three consecutive years.

Andrew Brunhart holds a Bachelor of Science degree in Electrical Engineering (magna cum laude) from Marquette University, a Master of Science degree in Electrical Engineering (Power) from the University of Illinois, and a Ph.D. in Public Policy and Administration (Leadership) from Walden University. He is a graduate of the Advanced Executive Program at the Kellogg Graduate School of Management at Northwestern University and holds a Certificate in Financial Planning. Andrew Brunhart is a licensed Professional Electrical Engineer (PE), a Registered Financial Consultant (RFC), and a former DoD Acquisition Professional (Contracting). He is a shareholder of the Green Bay Packers. His many military decorations include five Legions of Merit and seven Meritorious Service Medals. He is a member of Tau Beta Pi (Engineering), Eta Kappa Nu (Electrical Engineering), and Pi Alpha Alpha (Public Affairs and Administration) honor societies.

teams.name: Greg Limeberry
teams.loan_because:
Greg Limeberry of Salt Lake City, Utah, is a ski patrolman at Snowbird mountain.  He grew up in New Hartford, New York, playing hockey and skiing, continuing to do both through college.  After college, he moved out west to continue skiing and think more about what he wanted to do with his life.  He took a job as a ski lift attendant to make some money while he pondered his future, but instead he fell in love with the mountain, and never left.  Wanting to ski more, he took the training course to become a ski patrolman, and now can be found on the slopes of snowbird, rescuing skiers and keeping the mountain safe.  His job is his passion and he wouldn’t want to be doing anything else.

When Greg Limeberry isn’t skiing, he’s planning his next adventure trip.  He loves to travel, especially trips that involve adventure.  He has climbed Mt. McKinley in Alaska, hiked the Zion Narrows of Utah and backpacked the extensive trails of Glacier National Park in Montana, to name a few.  Greg Limeberry hopes to travel more within the USA, and perhaps take his adventurous spirit overseas to explore more of the world.  Greg Lives with his wife Angela and two bernese mountain dogs, Ella and Bear.

teams.name: Marc Blatstein
teams.loan_because: Marc Blatstein was born in Philadelphia, PA.  He went to Undergraduate College at George Washington University in Washington DC where he earned a BA in Psychology, all the time working to help with the high costs of a college education. This was followed with medical training at the Ohio College of Podiatric Medicine, where Marc Blatstein obtained a Doctor of Podiatric Medicine Degree. While he was here, he also worked to help with the costs of an education.  Marc had a surgical residency in Podiatric Medicine, which followed by a 22 year career as a single practitioner. While in practice he incorporated a medically oriented shoe store, wound care and physical therapy. A major part of Marc Blatstein’s practice is the use of The Circulator Boot™ as a method of treatment that supports the core elements of wound therapy: increased blood supply, bacterial control, moisture and debridement. Along with other modes of treatment, surgical debridement of infected wounds, the use of antibiotic medications, along with home care, boot therapy may improve the blood supply and control the infection in necrotizing cellulitis when standard methods of treatment are failing.

teams.loan_because: To alleviate poverty and hardship
teams.description:
We are a loosely affiliated group of people who come from a diverse range of backgrounds. Our common passion is the recognition that humans, as a species, have evolved alongside plants to get where we are today, and that we could not have done so without them (whether it be for food, medicine, spiritual or cultural development, shelter, or even just aesthetics). We cherish the ongoing roles these plants play in our lives, and defend our right to continue and nurture this relationship.

Lenders from this team make loans with the goal of improving the lives of people less fortunate than themselves. A significant portion of the funds raised for these loans come from selling, trading, and sharing plants, with the vision of further extending the growth these plants have brought to human existence.

teams.name: Family & Friends of Dr Dieter Roeschmann
teams.loan_because:
My dad joined the "computer age" a little late in the game, but when he did, he was fascinated be the possibilities it opened up - especially in the world of finance and investment. After he passed away all too sudden and early in 2012, I also discovered charitable giving side of him, I had previously not known. With his birthday approaching, I felt the urge to "give" something in his name, but nothing seemed appropriate. While he never got to experience micro-lending, I believe, the combination of technology, finance and helping people getting something started, would have gotten him quite excited, and I can picture him spending hours on Kiva, researching "worthy" loans.

We loan in my father's name in order to help entrepreneurs help themselves, and to carry on his legacy in spirit. Each team member is free to choose their own loans without restrictions, but as they do, we ask them to take a moment to commemoration my dad.

Thank you.

teams.name: Kiva Flash Mob
teams.loan_because:
we want to bring lenders from different teams together and show some Kiva love to loans have so far been overlooked. We want to help get them funded by organizing a Flash Mob to these loans.  

The effect of many lenders loaning to the same loan at the same time is that the loan will show up on page 1 of the popularity sort, which is the default page that most lenders look at when they come to Kiva. So besides the loans from the Flash Mob team, Flash Mob loans often attract many additional loans from other lenders who just happened to log into Kiva at this time. Sometimes a loan gets completely funded within the hour!

Feel free to keep attributing your loans to your favorite team, it is fun to see many different team logos on the same loan.
teams.description:
Primary Flash Mob time is 9am US West Coast / noon EST / 6pm MET / 4am AET

If you can't join the primary Flash Mob, a second Flash Mob time is 11pm US West Coast / 2am EST / 8am MET / 6pm AET

The loan will be posted an hour or two in advance to give you time to research it. For maximum Flash Mob impact, please try to loan exactly at Flash Mob time.

For email alerts with just the daily loan link, please join http://www.kiva.org/team/KFM_messages and set your email preferences for that team to immediate delivery. For a comprehensive description of the Flash Mob loan, to talk to other Flash Mobbers and to suggest loans, please join this team. 

Loans selected for the Flash Mob are typically within 2 weeks of expiration (preferably red-boxed) and completely unfunded or lacking a substantial amount. For suggestions please message the captains.

teams.description:
¿What is it all about?

AFRICAN CHILD INITIATIVE AND COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT FORUM is a community empowering programme working with self-help groups, income generating projects, host families, and the community in Kivaani location, Kangundo District, in Kenya, to support Government and donor efforts in order to eradicate poverty and improve the social and economic situation of the villagers.

We also work with the church, schools, and youth polytechnics as a focal point of civic education and modern communication networking. It is the forum where the villagers are making world wide contacts by hosting guests freely and exchanging cultural values. Our home stay programme have opened doors with contacts from all continents and in return some of our guests have participated in funding some of the community projects.

Furthermore we lobby for the african childhood who stay in the village and fight difficulties meeting their daily needs due to a certain disadvantage; for instance: if the child had lost one or both parents due to H.I.V./Aids or if the parents are too poor to afford offering the child the basic needs and education. Our popular programme called Omega Child is the core for formula for success and in order to support African Child in this programme we conduce long distance adoptions, talent search, placement at a children home, and other initiatives.

Our core values are networking and collaboration as a basis for acquiring and sharing cultural diversity. We advocate for community participation and resource mobilization, planning, monitoring and evaluation of the projects for the benefit of the community and the funding agents.

We indeed collaborate with young people, parents, teachers, professionals, community leaders and others the effort to empower young people and promote their contribution in the community around the issues of familiar planning, health, H.I.V./Aids, environment conservation, leadership, and any other key inter-related socioeconomic affairs. There are affiliated projects in the slums as some of those young people living in the village come to the city after school, in search of jobs hence having a new home in the slum after failing to secure any job in the city. At the moment we are encouraging them to come back to the village and help in mobilizing the available resources and participate within the project.

In summary, African child initiative has 4 key areas of intervention in the village:

    * Poverty eradication
    * Entrepreneurship encouraging
    * Community development
    * Education and learning with special emphasis in computer literacy

We identify critical issues that concern this villages, slums, and community and translate them into short term and long term programmes.


OUR MISSION

To approach community development from the grass roots.


OUR VISION

To advocate for self and community empowerment.


How can you be of help to our initiative?

    *

      You can make any form of contribution (materials, cash, skills and ideas) towards any of our numerous projects.
    *

      You can be part of the network, campaign or volunteer to work with one or any of our projects.
    *

      Be part of our cultural ambassadors by visiting our village and joining our cultural exchange programme.


Thadeus M. Mutisya

Executive Chairman
